## purpose
Defines the canonical architectural role of permission in CivilizationOS.

## design_intent
Permission is the bounded allowance structure
through which action scope,
resource scope,
delegation scope,
prohibition,
and effective authority
become meaningful.

Permission is not the same as identity or governance.
Identity says who,
governance says who decides,
permission says what is allowed within which scope.

## architectural_position
Permission sits between:
- identity continuity
- governance decision structure
- security enforcement
- runtime execution
- audit and denial logic

## required_behavior
- permission scope must remain explicit
- actor/resource/action scope must remain explicit
- delegation basis must remain explicit
- allow and deny states must remain distinguishable
- current and historical permission states must remain distinguishable

## canonical_rules
- delegation must not silently widen scope
- implied permission without basis is prohibited
- historical permission trace must remain queryable
- ambiguous permission scope fails closed

## state_model
The permission domain distinguishes:
- granted permission
- restricted permission
- delegated permission
- revoked permission
- historical permission

## actor_boundary
- grant source
- holder
- reviewer
- operator
- adapter

## decision_matrix
- if permission basis is unclear, stop permission-sensitive action
- if actor/resource/action scope is unclear, fail closed
- if delegation exceeds source scope, deny
- if permission becomes historical or revoked, preserve trace

## review_checklist
- permission basis is explicit
- scope model is explicit
- delegation model is explicit
- historical distinction is explicit
